courses.title: Differential Calculus with Applications to Physical Sciences and Engineering
courses.description: Derivatives of elementary functions. Applications and modelling: graphing, optimization.

courses.title: Integral Calculus with Applications to Physical Sciences and Engineering
courses.description: The definite integral, integration techniques, applications, modelling, infinite series.

courses.title: Differential Calculus with Applications to Life Sciences
courses.description: Functions, derivatives, optimization, growth and decay, discrete probability.

courses.title: Integral Calculus with Applications to Life Sciences
courses.description: Antiderivatives and definite integrals, infinite series, applications to probability and dynamical systems.

courses.title: Differential Calculus with Applications to Commerce and Social Sciences
courses.description: Derivatives and rates of change, exponential and trigonometric functions, Newton's method, Taylor polynomials, maxima and minima, and graphing.

courses.title: Integral Calculus with Applications to Commerce and Social Sciences
courses.description: Antiderivatives, the definite integral, techniques of integration, infinite series, partial derivatives, maxima and minima with constraints, discrete and continuous random variables.

courses.title: Differential Calculus
courses.description: Topics as for MATH 100, but including relevant topics from algebra, geometry, functions, trigonometry, logarithms, and exponentials.

courses.title: Honours Differential Calculus
courses.description: Limits, derivatives, Mean Value Theorem and applications, elementary functions, optimization, Taylor series, approximation.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Credit excluded with MATH 100, 102, 104, 110, 180, 184, SCIE 001.

courses.title: Honours Integral Calculus
courses.description: Definite integrals and the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, techniques and applications of integration, infinite series.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Credit excluded with MATH 101, 103, 105, SCIE 001.

courses.title: Linear Systems
courses.description: 2D and 3D geometry, vectors and matrices, eigenvalues and vibration, physical applications. Laboratories demonstrate computer solutions of large systems.
courses.notes: For Engineering students only. Credit excluded with MATH 221, 223.

courses.title: Differential Calculus with Physical Applications
courses.description: Topics as for Math 100; intended for students with no previous knowledge of Calculus.

courses.title: Differential Calculus for Social Science and Commerce
courses.description: Topics as for Math 104; intended for students with no previous knowledge of Calculus.

courses.title: Calculus Survey
courses.description: Functions, derivatives, integrals, curve sketching growth functions, volume calculations. Only for credit in the Faculty of Forestry.

courses.title: Calculus III
courses.description: Analytic geometry in 2 and 3 dimensions, partial and directional derivatives, chain rule, maxima and minima, second derivative test, Lagrange multipliers, multiple integrals with applications.

courses.title: Introduction to Mathematical Computing
courses.description: Introduction to numerical computation, computer algebra, mathematical graphics. Primarily for second year students taking a degree in mathematics.

courses.title: Elementary Differential Equations I
courses.description: First-order equations; linear equations; linear systems; Laplace transforms; numerical methods; trajectory analysis of plane nonlinear systems. Applications of these topics will be emphasized.

courses.title: Multivariable and Vector Calculus
courses.description: Partial differentiation, extreme values, multiple integration, vector fields, line and surface integrals, the divergence theorem, Green's and Stokes' theorems.
courses.notes: Intended for students in Honours Physics and Engineering Physics. Credit excluded with MATH 227, 254, 264, 317. Math students are advised to take MATH 317.

courses.title: Mathematical Proof
courses.description: Sets and functions; induction; cardinality; properties of the real numbers; sequences, series, and limits. Logic, structure, style, and clarity of proofs emphasized throughout.

courses.title: Matrix Algebra
courses.description: Systems of linear equations, operations on matrices, determinants, eigenvalues and eigenvectors, diagonalization of symmetric matrices.

courses.title: Linear Algebra
courses.description: Matrices, eigenvectors, diagonalization, orthogonality, linear systems, applications. Intended for Honours students.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Credit excluded with MATH 152, 221, 310.

courses.title: Advanced Calculus I
courses.description: Functions of several variables: limits, continuity, differentiability; implicit functions; Taylor's theorem; extrema; Lagrange multipliers; multiple integration, Fubini's theorem; improper integrals.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Credit excluded with MATH 200, 217, 253, 254.

courses.title: Advanced Calculus II
courses.description: Parametrization of curves and surfaces; line and surface integrals; theorems of Green, Gauss, Stokes; applications to physics and/or introduction to differential forms.

courses.title: Introduction to Finite Mathematics
courses.description: Difference equations, number theory, counting. Intended primarily for students not in the Faculty of Science who wish to have some exposure to mathematical thinking. Students who obtain credit for MATH 100, MATH 102, MATH 104, MATH 110, MATH 120, MATH 180, MATH 184, or SCIE 001 cannot in the same year or in later years obtain credit for MATH 230.

courses.title: Multivariable Calculus
courses.description: Partial and directional derivatives; maxima and minima; Lagrange multipliers and second derivative test; multiple integrals and applications.

courses.title: Multivariable and Vector Calculus for Mechanical Engineering
courses.description: Partial differentiation, extreme values, multiple integration, vector fields, line and surface integrals, the divergence and Stokes' theorems; applications to fluid mechanics: buoyancy, hydrostatic force, pipe flow, drag; applications to thermodynamics: work, entropy, heat transfer; numerical methods. Emphasis on mechanical engineering applications.
courses.notes: For Mechanical Engineering students only. Credit excluded with MATH 200, 217, 226, 227, 253, 254, 264, 317.

courses.title: Ordinary Differential Equations
courses.description: Review of linear systems; nonlinear equations and applications; phase plane analysis; Laplace transforms; numerical methods.
courses.notes: For Engineering students only. Cross-listed with MATH 215. Credit excluded with MATH 215, 256, 258

courses.title: Differential Equations
courses.description: Linear ordinary differential equations, Laplace transforms, Fourier series and separation of variables for linear partial differential equations.

courses.title: Partial Differential Equations
courses.description: Introduction to partial differential equations; Fourier series; the heat, wave and potential equations; boundary-value problems; numerical methods.
courses.notes: Credit excluded with MATH 316, 358, MECH 358, PHYS 312.

courses.title: Differential Equations for Mechanical Engineering
courses.description: First-order equations; linear equations; linear systems; Laplace transforms; trajectory analysis of plane nonlinear systems; translational and rotational vibrations; applications to RLC circuit analysis; numerical and graphical methods. Emphasis on mechanical engineering applications.
courses.notes: For Mechanical Engineering students only. Credit excluded with MATH 215, 255, 256.

courses.title: Vector Calculus for Electrical Engineering
courses.description: Divergence, gradient, curl, theorems of Gauss and Stokes. Applications to Electrostatics and Magnetostatics. MATH 264 content is strongly coupled to BMEG 220 and ELEC 211 with topics and student evaluations weighted accordingly. This course is not eligible for Credit/D/Fail grading.

courses.title: Introduction to Complex Variables
courses.description: Functions of a complex variable, Cauchy-Riemann equations, elementary functions, Cauchy's theorem and contour integration, Laurent series, poles and residues.

courses.title: Applied Analysis
courses.description: Integrals involving multi-valued functions, conformal mapping and applications, analytic continuation, Laplace and Fourier transforms.

courses.title: Introduction to Probability
courses.description: Basic notions of probability, random variables, expectation and conditional expectation, limit theorems.

courses.title: Introduction to Stochastic Processes
courses.description: Discrete-time Markov chains, Poisson processes, continuous time Markov chains, renewal theory.

courses.title: Applied Complex Analysis
courses.description: Functions of a complex variable, Cauchy-Riemann equations, contour integration, Laurent series, residues, integrals of multi-valued functions, Fourier transforms.
courses.notes: Intended for Engineering Physics students. Credit excluded with MATH 300. Math students are advised to take MATH 300.

courses.title: Applied Linear Algebra
courses.description: Applications of linear algebra to problems in science and engineering; use of computer algebra systems for solving problems in linear algebra.

courses.title: Euclidean Geometry
courses.description: Classical plane geometry, solid geometry, spherical trigonometry, polyhedra, linear and affine transformations. Linear algebra proofs are used. It is suggested that MATH 307 be taken concurrently.

courses.title: Topics in Geometry
courses.description: Topics chosen by the instructor. These may include conic sections, projective configuration, convexity, non-Euclidean geometries, fractal geometry, combinatorial problems of points in the plane.

courses.title: Abstract Linear Algebra
courses.description: Linear spaces, duality, linear mappings, matrices, determinant and trace, spectral theory, Euclidean structure.

courses.title: Introduction to Number Theory
courses.description: Euclidean algorithm, congruences, Fermat's theorem, applications. Some diophantine equations. Distribution of the prime numbers.

courses.title: Topics in Number Theory
courses.description: Topics chosen by the instructor. These might include: division algorithms, group theory, continued fractions, primality testing, factoring.

courses.title: Elementary Differential Equations II
courses.description: Power series methods (ordinary and regular singular points, Bessel's equation); boundary value problems and separation of variables (Fourier series and other orthogonal series), applications to the vibrating string, heat flow, potentials.
courses.notes: Credit excluded with MATH 257, 358, MECH 358, PHYS 312.

courses.title: Calculus IV
courses.description: Parametrizations, inverse and implicit functions, integrals with respect to length and area; grad, div, and curl, theorems of Green, Gauss, and Stokes.

courses.title: Probability with Physical Applications
courses.description: Random variables, discrete and continuous distributions. Random walk, Markov chains, Monte Carlo methods. Characteristic functions, limit laws.
courses.notes: Intended for students in Honours Physics and Engineering Physics. Credit excluded with MATH 302, STAT 302. Math students are advised to take MATH 302.

courses.title: Introduction to Real Analysis
courses.description: A rigorous introduction to the ideas and methods of real analysis and their application. This course is intended for Mathematics Majors students in a non-honours track.

courses.title: Real Variables I
courses.description: The real number system; real Euclidean n-space; open, closed, compact, and connected sets; Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem; sequences and series. Continuity and uniform continuity. Differentiability and mean-value theorems.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Credit excluded with MATH 319.

courses.title: Real Variables II
courses.description: The Riemann or Riemann-Stieltjes integrals. Sequences and series of functions, uniform convergence. Approximation of continuous functions by polynomials. Fourier series. Functions from Rm to Rn, inverse and implicit function theorems.

courses.title: Introduction to Group Theory
courses.description: Groups, cosets, homomorphisms, group actions, p-groups, Sylow theorems, composition series, finitely generated Abelian groups.

courses.title: Introduction to Rings and Modules
courses.description: Rings, ideals, unique factorization, Euclidean rings, fields, polynomial rings, modules; structure theory of modules over a principal ideal domain.

courses.title: Introduction to Mathematics
courses.description: Intensive course with required tutorial. Combinatorics, probability, geometry and elementary number theory. Not for credit in the Faculty of Science. Students who obtain credit at UBC for any other mathematics course cannot in the same or later years obtain credit for MATH 335.

courses.title: Introduction to Linear Programming
courses.description: Linear programming problems, dual problems, the simplex algorithm, solution of primal and dual problems, sensitivity analysis. Additional topics chosen from: Karmarkar's algorithm, non-linear programming, game theory, applications.

courses.title: Introduction to Discrete Mathematics
courses.description: Introduction to ideas and methods of discrete mathematics and their application.

courses.title: Algebra and Coding Theory
courses.description: Error-correcting codes via abstract and linear algebra. Emphasis on proofs and computation. Finite fields, Hamming distance and error-correction, upper and lower bounds on the size of a code, linear codes, groups and cosets, encoding and decoding schemes.

courses.title: Mathematical Game Theory
courses.description: Introduction to mathematical game theory and its applications.

courses.title: Applied Nonlinear Dynamics and Chaos
courses.description: Phase plane methods, bifurcation and stability theory, limit-cycle behavior and chaos for nonlinear differential equations with applications to the sciences. Assignments involve the use of computers.

courses.title: Engineering Analysis
courses.description: Fourier series; auto- and cross-correlation; power spectra; discrete Fourier transform; boundary-value problems; numerical methods; partial differential equations; heat, wave, Laplace, Poisson, and wave equations. Applications to mechanical engineering and practical computing applications emphasized. Credit will be granted for only one of MECH 358 or MATH 358.
courses.notes: Intended for Mechanical Engineering students. Cross-listed with MECH 358. Credit excluded with MATH 257, 316, MECH 358, PHYS 312.

courses.title: Introduction to Mathematical Modelling
courses.description: Construction and evaluation of deterministic, stochastic, and data- driven models. Numerical solutions of ordinary differential equations, simulations of stochastic processes, and implementations of basic machine learning algorithms. Examples from science, engineering, and economics. Solutions by mathematical software.

courses.title: Introduction to Mathematical Biology
courses.description: Mathematical modelling of basic biological processes in ecology, physiology, neuroscience and genetics. Dynamic behavior of difference equations, differential equations, and partial differential equations, explained with reference to concrete biological examples.

courses.title: Applied Partial Differential Equations
courses.description: Separation of variables, first order equations, Sturm-Liouville theory, integral transform methods.

courses.title: Green's Functions and Variational Methods
courses.description: Green's functions for partial differential equations. Calculus of variations. Eigenfunction expansions. Rayleigh-Ritz and finite element methods.

courses.title: Calculus of Variations
courses.description: Classical variational problems; necessary conditions of Euler, Weierstrass, Legendre, and Jacobi; Erdmann corner conditions, transversality, convex Lagrangians, fields of extremals, sufficient conditions for optimality, numerical methods; applications to classical mechanics, engineering and economics.

courses.title: Stabilization and Optimal Control of Dynamical Systems
courses.description: Dynamical systems; stability by Liapunov's direct method; controllability and eigenvalue assignment for autonomous linear systems; linear-quadratic regulator, time optimal control, Pontryagin maximum principle, dynamic programming; applications in engineering, economics and resource management.

courses.title: Harmonic Analysis I
courses.description: Harmonic analysis on Euclidean spaces, with applications to number theory, partial differential equations and geometric measure theory.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 541.

courses.title: Numerical Methods for Differential Equations
courses.description: Interpolation, numerical integration, numerical solution of ordinary and partial differential equations. Practical computational methods emphasized and basic theory developed through simple models.

courses.title: Variational and Approximate Methods in Applied Mathematics
courses.description: Variational and Green's function methods for ordinary and partial differential equations, introduction to finite difference, finite element and boundary element methods.
courses.notes: Intended for Engineering Physics students. Credit excluded with MATH 401, 405. Math students are advised to take MATH 401, 405.

courses.title: Advanced Linear Algebra
courses.description: Topics include decompositions of linear operators, multi linear algebra, bilinear forms, metric spaces.

courses.title: Probability
courses.description: Probability spaces, random variables, distributions, expectation, conditional probabilities, convergence of random variables, generating and characteristic functions, weak and strong laws of large numbers, central limit theorem.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 544.

courses.title: Stochastic Processes
courses.description: Random walks, Markov chains, branching processes, Poisson processes, continuous time Markov chains, martingales, Brownian motion.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 545.

courses.title: Real Analysis I
courses.description: Sigma-algebras, Lebesgue measure, Borel measures, measurable functions, integration, convergence theorems, Lp spaces, Holder and Minkowski inequalities, Lebesgue and/or Radon-Nikodym differentiation.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 507.

courses.title: Real Analysis II
courses.description: Banach spaces, linear operators, bounded and compact operators, strong, weak, and weak* topology. Hahn-Banach, open mapping, and closed graph theorems. Hilbert spaces, symmetric and self-adjoint operators, spectral theory for bounded operators.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 510.

courses.title: Fields and Galois Theory
courses.description: Field extensions, the Galois correspondence, finite fields, insolvability in radicals, ruler and compass constructions, additional topics chosen by instructor.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 501.

courses.title: Commutative Algebra
courses.description: Commutative algebra; homological algebra or representation theory of finite groups.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 502.

courses.title: Classical Differential Geometry
courses.description: The differential geometry of curves and surfaces in three-dimensional Euclidean space. Mean curvature and Gaussian curvature. Geodesics. Gauss's Theorema Egregium.

courses.title: Introduction to Modern Differential Geometry
courses.description: Riemannian manifolds, tensors and differential forms, curvature and geodesics.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 525.

courses.title: Introduction to Topology
courses.description: General topology, combinatorial topology, fundamental group and covering spaces, topics chosen by the instructor.

courses.title: Topics in Topology
courses.description: Homology theory, homotopy theory, manifolds, and other topics chosen by the instructor.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 527.

courses.title: Mathematical Classical Mechanics I
courses.description: Newton's equation, conservation laws, the Euler-Lagrange equation; Hamilton's principle of least action, Hamilton's equations, Lagrangian mechanics on manifolds.

courses.title: Number Theory
courses.description: Divisibility, congruences, Diophantine equations, arithmetic functions, quadratic reciprocity, advanced topics.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 537. Credit excluded with MATH 312, 313.

courses.title: Complex Analysis
courses.description: The residue theorem, the argument principle, conformal mapping, the maximum modulus principle, harmonic functions, representation of functions by integrals, series, and products. Other topics at the discretion of the instructor.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 508.

courses.title: Mathematical Modelling: Discrete Optimization Problems
courses.description: Formulation of real-world optimization problems using techniques such as linear programming, network flows, integer programming, dynamic programming. Solution by appropriate software.

courses.title: Graphs and Networks
courses.description: Graph theory, emphasizing trees, tree growing algorithms, and proof techniques. Other topics chosen from shortest paths, maximum flows, minimum cost flows, matchings, and graph colouring.

courses.title: Graph Theory
courses.description: Introductory course in mostly non-algorithmic topics including: planarity and Kuratowski's theorem, graph colouring, graph minors, random graphs, cycles in graphs, Ramsey theory, extremal graph theory. Proofs emphasized. Intended for Honours students.

courses.title: Mathematical Research and Writing
courses.description: Current research topics in pure and applied mathematics are explored at the undergraduate level. Technical communication and research skills are developed.

courses.title: Topics in the History of Mathematics I
courses.description: Historical development of concepts and techniques in areas chosen from Geometry, Number Theory, Algebra, Calculus, Probability, Analysis. The focus is on historically significant writings of important contributors and on famous problems of Mathematics.

courses.title: Asymptotic and Perturbation Methods
courses.description: Asymptotic expansions. Asymptotic evaluation of integrals; WKBJ methods. Regular and singular expansions. Boundary layer theory; matched asymptotic expansions. Multiple scale techniques.
courses.notes: Intended for Honours students. Cross-listed with MATH 550.

courses.title: Projects in Mathematical Biology
courses.description: Development and analysis of mathematical models for complex systems in ecology, evolution, cell biology, neurophysiology, and other biological and medical disciplines.

courses.title: Projects in Computational Mathematics
courses.description: To be offered in 2024/2025

programs.name: All Courses
programs.description1: The UBC Department of Mathematics offers a wide range of undergraduate courses from calculus to number theory to mathematical biology. Explore the different programs of study including BA/BSc Major in Mathematics, BA/BSc Honours in Mathematics, and courses offered for engineering programs.
programs.description2: The course map presents all MATH courses along with prerequisite/corequisite connections. Hover over a course to view the course description, a complete list of prerequisites/corequisites, credit exclusions and notes. Complete information is available in the UBC Academic Calendar and current course offerings are available in the UBC Course Schedule.

programs.name: Major in Mathematics
programs.description1: After completing 100 and 200 level degree requirements, students in the BA/BSc Major in Mathematics program choose any 24 credits of MATH courses numbered 300 and above. Certain courses work especially well together. Math majors are strongly recommended to select all the courses in one of the five listed streams. Complete degree requirements are available in the UBC Academic Calendar.
programs.description2:
Degree requirements for BA/BSc Major in Mathematics include:
• Calculus I (MATH 100, 102, 104, 180, 184, 110 or 120)
• Calculus II (MATH 101, 103, 105 or 121)
• Calculus III (MATH 200, 217 or 226)
• Mathematical Proof (MATH 220)
• Linear Algebra (MATH 221 or 223)
• Differential Equations (MATH 215)
• Mathematical Computing (MATH 210 or CPSC 210)
• 24 credits of MATH courses numbered 300 or above

programs.name: Honours in Mathematics
programs.description1:
Degree requirements for BA/BSc Honours in Mathematics are listed in the UBC Academic Calendar. First and second year requirements are:
• Calculus I (MATH 100, 102, 104, 180, 184, 110 or 120)
• Calculus II (MATH 101, 103, 105 or 121)
• Calculus III (MATH 200, 217 or 226)
• Calculus IV (MATH 317 or 227)
• Linear Algebra (MATH 221 or 223)
• Differential Equations (MATH 215)
• Mathematical Computing (MATH 210 or CPSC 210)
programs.description2:
Third and fourth year requirements include:
• MATH 300 Complex Analysis
• MATH 320 Real Variables I
• MATH 321 Real Variables II
• MATH 322 Introduction to Group Theory
• MATH 323 Introduction to Rings and Modules
• 15 credits from MATH 400-406, 412, 418-428, 433-440, 443, 449, 450
• Additional 9 credits of MATH courses numbered 300 or above

programs.name: Engineering Courses
programs.description1: Engineering courses are designed for specific applications and are reserved for APSC students.

tracks.name: Differential Equations and Analysis
tracks.description1:
This stream is centred on the analysis of functions and the phenomena they describe, from quantum mechanics to celestial motion. Topics in this stream have many applications in physics and engineering. If you like calculus and want to learn about some of its most important applications, this stream is for you.

Courses: MATH 300, 301, 316, 400, 317, 319
tracks.description2:
Degree requirements for BA/BSc Major in Mathematics include:
• Calculus I (MATH 100, 102, 104, 180, 184, 110 or 120)
• Calculus II (MATH 101, 103, 105 or 121)
• Calculus III (MATH 200, 217 or 226)
• Mathematical Proof (MATH 220)
• Linear Algebra (MATH 221 or 223)
• Differential Equations (MATH 215)
• Mathematical Computing (MATH 210 or CPSC 210)
• 24 credits of MATH courses numbered 300 or above

tracks.name: Mathematical Computing
tracks.description1:
This stream is centred on solving problems using numerical techniques and approximations. Topics in this stream have many applications in engineering, economics and computing. If you like solving math problems using software and programming, this stream is for you.

Courses: MATH 307, 316, 405, 340, 441, 360, 461

Suggested courses from other departments: CPSC 302, 303, 402, 406
tracks.description2:

tracks.name: Mathematics of Data
tracks.description1:
This stream is centred on the theoretical foundations of data science. Topics in this stream have many applications in machine learning and signal processing. If you like algorithms and making sense of large data sets, this stream is for you.

Courses: MATH 302, 303, 307, 340, 441, 344 and 442

Suggested courses from other departments: CPSC 340, 440; PHIL 320, 321

tracks.name: Mathematical Modelling
tracks.description1:
This stream is centred on constructing and evaluating mathematical models. Topics in this stream have many applications in science, especially in mathematical biology and computational mathematics for physical problems. If you like multidisciplinary work and using mathematics to describe real-world problems, this stream is for you.

Courses: MATH 302, 303, 344, 345, 360+461 or 361+462

Suggested courses from other departments: CPSC 330, 421; PHIL 321
tracks.description2:

• Mathematical Proof (MATH 220)
• Linear Algebra (MATH 221 or 223)

• Mathematical Computing (MATH 210 or CPSC 210)
• 24 credits of MATH courses numbered 300 or above

tracks.name: Structures: Number Theory and Geometry
tracks.description1:
This stream is centred on classical problems in two of the most enduring branches of mathematics. Topics in this stream have modern applications in areas including cryptography and computer graphics. If you like patterns and puzzles, this stream is for you.

Courses: MATH 310, 341, 342, 308+309 or 312+313

Suggested courses from other departments: CPSC 424; PHIL 320, 322, 323, 420
